post_text:
Five ASD students have worked throughout the summer to design a prototype for the TI/NASA Codes Contest. The challenge for this year was to automate something on the International Space Station, using TI technology. These students choose a project that would free up time the astronauts would normally need to spend on chores, so they could focus on more important tasks. This video was the submission for the 3rd phase of the contest, and now they wait to see if they've made the finals. Please join us in congratulating them on their ingenuity, hard work, and collaboration!

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ovFFQW7_wgg

NASA - National Aeronautics and Space Administration was live.
August 2 at 7:54 AM ·

After 62 days in space, approximately 1,024 orbits around our planet and four spacewalks, our #LaunchAmerica crew members are on their way home!

Watch our live coverage Sunday, Aug. 2, starting at 7:25 a.m. EDT to see NASA Astronauts Robert Behnken and Douglas Hurley, aboard SpaceX’s Crew Dragon Endeavour spacecraft, on their journey back to Earth. Splashdown in the Gulf of Mexico off the coast of Pensacola, Florida is currently targeted for 2:48 p.m. EDT.

post_text: This morning three students from ASD along with Amy Bewley (faculty advisor for the students who are a part of this) were able to attend the Bridges House Youth Sustainability Council UNH Sustainability Expo that was planned for today virtually. The Bridges House Sustainability Council was started by New Hampshire's First Lady Sununu in partnership with Project Green Schools to bring together environmentally-conscious middle and high school students from across the Granite State. ASD is proud to have three of our sophomores as a part of this worthwhile endeavor. Photo from October 26, 2019.

post_text: Do you know of or work for a company that may be able to use student interns remotely? post_text: Recently ASD student Arabella (violinist) and her sister, Alessandra (former ASD student) initiated a benefit concert for the victims of the Taal Volcano eruption in the Philippines. They were joined in by 5 other ASD students: Caitlyn and Jacquelyn (vocalists), Christian (videographer & logistics), Matthew (piano) and Jaymier (saxophone). Other young musicians in the community also participated. They joined forces in sharing their gift of music to raise funds, raise awareness and inspire others to help. They were able to raise money that will be given to the victims of Taal Volcano.

shared_text:
Academy for Science and Design Charter School added 5 new photos.
February 18 at 3:57 PM ·

The BAE Systems Women in Technology (WiT) program started at the company’s Nashua campus 25 years ago. The annual graduation ceremony was held on Tuesday, February 18, 2020, at Sky Meadow Country Club, honoring the 24 young women from high schools around the region who completed the engineering exploration program this year. The WiT program objective is to allow female students in high school who have an aptitude in math and science a practical, hands-on opportunity to explore careers in various technical disciplines. It also provides mentorship to the students to encourage and support them in their pursuit of a technical career. Congratulations to all of the WiT class of 2020 graduates, especially ASD’s own Sarah, Olivia, Grace and Nicole!

The WiT program objective is to allow female students in high school who have an aptitude in math and science a practical, hands-on opportunity to explore careers in various technical disciplines. It also provides mentorship to the students to encourage and support them in their pursuit of a technical career. Congratulations to all of the WiT class of 2020 graduates, especially ASD’s own Sarah, Olivia, Grace and Nicole!

shared_text:
P2A.CO
NH Students Need Your Support!

NH Alliance for Public Charter Schools
February 15 at 7:54 AM ·

On Tuesday, February 18, the Senate Finance Committee will hold a public hearing on Senate Bill SB747-FN (SB747-FN). If passed, this bill would allow the New Hampshire Department of Education to accept the first installment of over $46 million dollars in federal grant funds destined for New Hampshire public schools. To date, acceptance of these federal funds have been blocked because of partisan politics. SB747 can remedy this travesty and help thousands of New Hampshire neediest students.

If passed, this bill would allow the New Hampshire Department of Education to accept the first installment of over $46 million dollars in federal grant funds destined for New Hampshire public schools. To date, acceptance of these federal funds have been blocked because of partisan politics. SB747 can remedy this travesty and help thousands of New Hampshire neediest students.

post_text: ASD Community: for your planning purposes, we are reaching out this afternoon to let you know that ASD will observe a 2 Hour Delay tomorrow, Friday, February 14th. The Nashua School District has also called a 2-Hour Delay for tomorrow due to the expected freezing temperatures and potential of black ice during the usual morning commute.
